It is possible for the new coronavirus to become a chronic, long lived human disease like influenza, and we need to be prepared for that, Wang Chen, a respiratory and critical care specialist at the Chinese Academy of Engineering, said in a recent interview.

Perhaps in agreement with this judgment, a growing number of drug companies and research institutions are joining the ranks of research and development of new coronavirus vaccines and specific drugs.

One aspect of the race that has accelerated the human race is the complete structural elucidation of the new coronavirus receptor ACE2 and the structure elucidation of the complex of the s protein and ACE2 on the new coronavirus surface.

"In the process of SARS and new coronavirus entering the body, ACE2 acts as a 'door handle' , grabbing it and opening the door to cells, " explains Zhou Qiang's team at the University of the West Lake.

Recently, perspective of this "door handle" of the important research, will come from this laboratory.

The research paper, "Structural basis for the recognition of the SARS-CoV-2 by full-length Human Ace2, " was published online at around 10:00 a.m. EDT on March 4,2020, this is the first time that Zhou Qiang's team has successfully analyzed the full length three dimensional structure of COVID-192 in cell surface receptor, and the three dimensional structure of the s protein receptor binding domain on the surface of COVID-19 and the full length protein complex of cell surface receptor ACE2, further unlocking the mystery of the invasion of human cells by the new coronavirus.

"first, we have seen for the first time the structure of the full-length host cell receptor ACE2 and the presence of ACE2 as a dimer, " Zhou Qiang explained in an exclusive interview with Deeptech. Previous work has only addressed a portion of the structure of ACE2, which is a monomer state due to the lack of a domain that mediates dimerization. It's as if you thought it worked with one hand, but it actually worked with both hands, increasing our understanding of how it works. We then analyzed the receptor-binding domain of the virus s protein and the full-length ACE2 complex to see how they interact, which could provide a good reference for the design of targeted drugs."

Over the past two years, the lab has been studying the structure and function of human amino acid transporter complexes, and has identified several target proteins, including ACE2. After the outbreak of new crown pneumonia, the team quickly raised the priority of ACE2 research, to achieve the fastest results, for drug development later provided key information.

Before the two studies, Westlake University was one of the few universities in China with a top freeze electron microscope platform. "since the establishment of Westlake University, we have successfully set up the frozen electron microscope platform in the shortest time, and have two KRIOS + K3 electron microscope equipments which are the most advanced in the world. This has laid the hardware foundation for us to analyze the structure of these complexes successfully. " Zhou Qiang said.

In 2015, the journal Nature Method named frozen electron microscopy the most interesting technology of the year. Over the past few years, Cryo-electron microscopy has emerged as an important research tool in structural biology.

The three pioneers of frozen electron microscopy also won the 2017 Nobel Chemistry Prize for their exploration and development of frozen electron microscopy.

With the development of freeze electron microscopy, the structures of various biomacromolecules can be accurately analyzed in near physiological state. But it's worth pointing out that in this viral "war of detection" , it's not always possible to have a frozen electron microscope. Because one of the key prerequisites for the effectiveness of freeze electron microscopy is the successful preparation of high-quality samples.

"The biggest challenge in this study is to obtain a stable full-length ACE2 protein, " Zhou Qiang explained. Without a good sample, it would be difficult to have a powerful freeze electron microscope. ACE2 is a membrane protein, and it is difficult to obtain a stable full-length ACE2 protein under normal conditions. With the accumulation of previous studies, we successfully stabilized the protein by co-expression of B0AT1 and ACE2, and finally analyzed its structure.

Like many of the other teams involved in the outbreak, Zhou Qiang quickly moved on to the next phase of research after both results were published. It is understood that the team's next research direction will be to further explore the interaction between ACE2 and new coronavirus s protein, but also actively cooperate with other researchers in other fields.
